<center>Magelo: <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=102563">Kogur</a></center> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/usalenie.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Salenie</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 255<br> <font color=#E9D756>(4/1/02 1:43:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3233.topic&index=22>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Gravethumb's PoS rules for PoG raid =P</span><hr size=1> As the official loot mistress of any Clan Battle Axe raid, I am the one who gets to follow and utilize the rules Siilverain posted above.  From what I've seen of the original complaint, I would have done it exactly the same way.  Here is what I see:<br>
<br>
/auc soandso says, &quot;Monk headband on treant thingee&quot;<br>
/auc Salenie says, &quot;Now taking /tells for monk helm.&quot;<br>
(crickets)<br>
/auc Salenie says, &quot;Now taking /tells for monk helm.&quot;<br>
(crickets)<br>
/auc Salenie says, &quot;Now taking /tells for monk helm.  Last call.&quot;<br>
Monk1 tells you: I would like the head wrap.<br>
/auc Monk bracer defaults to Monk1.<br>
<br>
At that point a make a notation on my grid next to my keyboard to Monk1's name that reads &quot;helm&quot; and move on to the next piece, combat, or what have you.<br>
<br>
Now when the next non BP piece drops for monks (we put legs in with all the others), lets say the bracer, Monk1 is out of the roll.  Why?  Why do we exclude Monk1 because he took a piece no one else wanted?  Why prevent him from rolling on nice piece when all he has so far is the crap piece?<br>
<br>
Because our raids are NBG.  NEED before greed.  You are only suppose to /tell us if the item is something you want; that you will use.  I like to think I am a talented loot mistress.  I have been asked to loot mistress raids based upon reputation only.  However, psychic abilities are not part of my forte' at this time.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Therefore, when I see <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Monk1 tells you: I would like the head wrap.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> I assume the following:  1)  That he listened to the loot rules when I went over them.  I always go over them.  Gives the players something to read while leader is making groups. 2)  The the head wrap is an upgrade for him.  I explain need before greed, and I say specifically, &quot;Do not tell me for an item if it is nothing something that you would use, on this character, as an improvement of what you have already.&quot;<br>
<br>
That is why Monk1 is out of the roll.  He has an item that he wanted already, while Monk2 has gotten squat.  Monk2 is on the raid as well, and he deserves a fair chance at the reward.  Monk1 has already been rewarded, so now it is Monk2's turn.  The wrist wrappings default to Monk2 (assuming no Monk3) and now both have won something and both can roll on the next non-BP item to drop.<br>
<br>
Yes, people on my raids have been burned by this.  They asked to be on a roll for a PoS because no one else wanted it, they win it, then they can't roll on ubah weapon that drops next.  While I do feel a little sympathy for them that they are stuck with something they didn't want, that sympathy is not very large because if it is a CBA hosted raid, the rules were postedand I went over them before we ported up/entered zone/what have you.<br>
<br>
I refuse to spoon feed raiders.  I am handling every loot in the raid, keeping records of who got what, fielding every loot question, trying to type stats of items as they fall, monitor timers on decaying corpses for no_drop items, tell people loot rules as they enter the raid (so they know what they are) and let us not forget, trying to fight effectively at the same time.  All they have to do is fight and read.  If they cannot be bothered to pay attention on loot rules which is 90% of the reason to go on a pickup raid anyway then they are gonna get stuck with the PoS loot.<br>
<br>
And all of it can be avoided with a simple /tell:  Monk1 tells you, &quot;No one is interested in the head band, can I loot it but not have it count?&quot;  At that point my answer is yes, they get the head band, and can still roll on the wrist wrap when it drops.  Just common sense really.<br>
<br>
